<F P=102>  LD2102162494 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1524 GMT 21 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2102162494 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, 21 Feb (TANJUG) -- Two radars for the 
detection of the location of artillery fire have been flown to 
Sarajevo airport, TANJUG learned today from Belgrade UNPROFOR 
[UN Protection Forces] headquarters. 
  The radars will "cover" Mt. Igman and the territory 
northeast 
and southeast of Sarajevo and will be able to locate the 
positions from which the cease-fire is violated, it is learned 
at the Belgrade UNPROFOR headquarters. 
  UNPROFOR radio reports that after a long period of tension a 
certain sense of relief is felt today in Sarajevo and that 
General Michael Rose has said that the warring parties in the 
former Yugoslav Republic [of Bosnia-Herzegovina] have placed 268 
artillery pieces under the "blue helmet's" control at nine 
locations. 

