<F P=100> SLOVENIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Parliament Caps Funds for Defense Spending </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2202191294 Ljubljana Radio Slovenia Network in Slovene 
1430 GMT 22 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU2202191294 </F>
<F P=104>  Ljubljana Radio Slovenia Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Slovene </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] The State Chamber today determined the funds 
for education and defense, which form integral parts of the 1994 
budget. Amendments to the Citizenship Law have been passed, too. 
Vesna Burnik reports: 
  [Begin Burnik recording] [passage omitted] Let us now 
concentrate on the most important decisions of today which will 
also have political consequences. 
  The funds for education are known -- 27.5 billion tolars 
will 
be spent over the next six years on educational buildings, 
improvement of computer literacy, textbooks, school food, and 
foreign languages. [passage omitted] 
  The State Chamber has irrevocably ruled that not more than 
76.6 billion tolars will be spent on investments in defense over 
the next 10 years. It was also decided that the Defense 
Ministry will be allowed to spend a maximum of 8.8. billion 
tolars per year. This decision was supported by present 
deputies of the United List, the Liberal Democratic Party, the 
Democratic Party, and the Ecological Party, who also opposed the 
government proposal of defense funds which would amount to 
slightly less than 85 billion tolars that will be mostly spent 
over five years. The government coalition has again split on 
this issue, as the Christian Democrats and Jansa's Social 
Democrats voted in favor of the government proposal and against 
the lower sum. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

