<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Danger of `Open Clash' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2402115394 Belgrade Radio Beograd Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1100 GMT 24 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU2402115394 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade Radio Beograd Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Zeljko Mandic report] </F>
  [Text] Since last night Western Slavonija has been cut off 
from the rest of the world. During the course of the night 
members of the peace forces blocked key positions on the 
Okucani-Gradiska upon Sava road with armored personnel carriers 
and infantry, preventing pedestrians and vehicles from passing 
through, thus bringing the crisis that has emerged near the Sava 
bridge to its most extreme stage, one that threatens to become 
an open clash between the UN Protection Forces [UNPROFOR] and 
the Serbian people of Western Slavonija. 
  At this moment are 10 UN armored personnel carriers on the 
highway, near a place called Dubovacki Nadloznjak. When asked 
who ordered the latest show of force, sadly not the only one, 
the UNPROFOR members replied that this was the order of the 
peacekeepers' supreme command. 
  Let us recap, UNPROFOR command yesterday issued an ultimatum 
to the Krajina police to surrender control of the bridge on the 
Sava River that links the republic of Serbian Krajina [RSK] and 
the Serbian region of Western Slavonija with the Srpska republic 
to the UN forces. This deadline expires today. 
  The RSK government's ultimatum was that the members of the 
Jordanian, Nepalese, and Argentinian Battalions must withdraw 
their men and military hardware from the Okucani-Gradiska upon 
Sava road within 24 hours and this deadline expired at 1900 
[1800 GMT] yesterday. 
  This latest action of violence by the Blue Berets has only 
complicated the already critical situation in Western Slavonija 
that has emerged in connection with control over the bridge on 
the Sava River linking Stara Gradiska and Gradiska upon Sava, 
which threatens to escalate and may result in clashes. 
  For the time being, we have not observed a concentration of 
new troops from other UN Protected Areas [UNPA] in the region, 
beside those who regrouped from some parts in UNPA Sector West. 
It has been learned, however, that there have been indications 
that the existing UNPROFOR troops in the crisis zone of Western 
Slavonija could be strengthened by additional forces. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

