<H3> <TI>   Serb General Denies Army Fired on Swedish Unit </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2302115894 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1042 GMT 23 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2302115894 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Zvornik, 23 Feb (TANJUG)--Major General Manojlo 
Milovanovic, chief of staff of the main headquarters of the 
Srpska republic army, told TANJUG today that the Serb side had 
not opened fire on members of UNPROFOR's [UN Protection Forces] 
Swedish unit yesterday. 
  "According to coordinates given by Gen. Angus Ramsey, 
UNPROFOR's chief of staff for former Bosnia-Herzegovina, it is 
clear that this attack launched from antiaircraft weapons could 
have not been launched by the Srpska republic army," Milovanovic 
said. 
  UNPROFOR said that the attack took place at the village of 
Ribnica (coordinates 9010), four kms northeast of Kakanj; the 
nearest Serb position is 22 kms as the crow flies, he stressed. 
  "Despite indisputable facts, Gen. Ramsey threatened on 
several occasions last night and yesterday that he would 
personally authorize NATO air strikes on Serbs," Gen. 
Milovanovic said. 
  However, he added, Gen. Michael Rose, commander of UNPROFOR 
in former Bosnia-Herzegovina, reacted adequately and demanded a 
detailed investigation of yesterday's incident. 
  "I am certain that the investigation will confirm that the 
Serb side did not fire on the Swedes," Milovanovic said. 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

