<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Resisting Units Finally Withdraw </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2302202694 Paris AFP in English 1934 GMT 23 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2302202694 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Pale, Bosnia-Herzegovina, Feb 23 (AFP) -- Three 
Bosnian Serb units who resisted putting their heavy arms under 
UN control in the Sarajevo region for three days finally 
withdrew the weapons on orders of their headquarters, a Bosnian 
Serb general said Wednesday. 
  Dusan Kovacevic, the Bosnian Serbs' "defense minister," told 
AFP the problem was resolved peacefully late Tuesday at Osijek, 
near Ilidza, a western suburb of the Bosnian capital, after the 
units received orders from their military headquarters. 
  "These arms were withdrawn deep into our territory, not to 
any particular destination, and will not be used at any point 
along the front unless the Moslems (Moslem-led Bosnian 
government forces) launch a general offensive against the 
Serbs," the general said. 
  He denied reports in Sarajevo that the Serbs had moved the 
arms toward the Olovo front, 60 kilometers (35 miles) north of 
Sarajevo, where fierce clashes broke out between Serbs and 
Moslems in November and December. 
  Journalists who witnessed the settlement said the soldiers 
had refused to turn in their weapons unless UN peacekeepers 
deployed along the front line. 
  The confrontation began Sunday, in the run-up to the 
expiration of a NATO-imposed deadline to Bosnian Serbs to 
withdraw their weapons from around Sarajevo or put them under UN 
control by midnight GMT, or face air strikes. 
  The recalcitrant units were based at Ilidza, Grbavica, the 
only part of central Sarajevo under Serb control, and in the 
northern part of the front lines. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

