<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Many Serb Positions Still Not Under Control </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2302162694 Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1400 GMT 23 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU2302162694 </F>
<F P=104>  Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] UN helicopters, which have been overflying the 
hills around Sarajevo for the past 48 hours, have discovered 66 
sites occupied by the Serbian aggressor's heavy artillery. The 
UN Protection Forces [UNPROFOR] patrols on the ground have 
discovered another 55 similar sites. Frozen guns and howitzers 
are located in many of these sites, and several days will be 
needed to haul them away. 
  According to UNPROFOR representative Colonel Bill Aikman, 
another 12 sites with Serbian artillery have still not been 
placed under control, although this should have been 
accomplished before the expiration of the deadline in the night 
from Sunday to Monday. Colonel Aikman said that two incidents 
with Karadzic's Serbs had occurred yesterday. The Serbs came to 
two sites and demanded that they be allowed to haul away the 
heavy artillery. After the UNPROFOR soldiers had refused to 
allow them to do so, they withdrew without causing further 
problems. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

