<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Muslims To Demand Other Troops With Russians </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2302140194 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1316 GMT 23 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2302140194 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, Feb 23 (TANJUG) -- Moslems in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina will, according to their leader Alija 
Izetbegovic, demand that following the arrival of the Russian 
peace-keepers troops from other countries come and join UNPROFOR 
[UN Protection Force]. 
  "If the Russians can come, then why should not the Turks 
also 
come," Izetbegovic said in the Vrijeme Ratno program of the 
Moslem television in Sarajevo. 
  Four hundred Russian peace-keeping troops have been in the 
Sarajevo area since Sunday. 
  The Russian peace-keepers came on the basis of an agreement 
between Bosnian Serbs and Moscow in order to secure ceasefire 
following the withdrawal of heavy artillery of the Bosnian Serb 
republic agreed on February 9 with UNPROFOR and the Moslem side. 
  Commenting the arrival of the Russian peace-keepers, 
Izetbegovic said he "trusts them as much as he does (trust) 
UNPROFOR." 
  Izetbegovic said the Moslems have accepted the arrangement 
for Sarajevo because it "has already been agreed it (Sarajevo) 
will be placed under U.N. administration" and that this formula 
will be applied to Mostar, the site of Moslem-Croat fighting in 
southwestern Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  According to him, the Moslem government will, when other 
towns are concerned, "think twice whether it will accept the 
formula since it could freeze the actual situation in the field." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

