<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Karadzic Writes Butrus-Ghali on UN in Sarajevo </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2402130294 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1211 GMT 24 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2402130294 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, 24 Feb (TANJUG) -- President of the Srpska 
republic Radovan Karadzic today called on UN Secretary General 
Butrus-Ghali to use his influence on the Security Council and 
prevent the adoption of a resolution on UN administration of 
Sarajevo before details on that issue have been agreed upon at 
the Geneva peace negotiations on Bosnia. At the same time the 
Bosnian Serb leader appealed to Butrus-Ghali to speed up these 
negotiations. 
  In a letter to Butrus-Ghali, a copy of which was forwarded 
to 
TANJUG today, Karadzic recalls that the Bosnian Muslims refused 
to talk about the UN administration of Sarajevo at the last 
round of Geneva talks. Therefore, according to him, the Serb 
side believes that the UN Security Council resolution ought not 
to precede negotiations on that issue in Geneva. "Otherwise, a 
solution which would be unacceptable for any one side could 
create obstacles for the peace process." 
  Karadzic said that "the peace process in Sarajevo is 
proceeding according to plan," and that the Sarajevo model, if 
successfully applied in the future, could serve as a useful 
model for other parts of former Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  "The cease-fire which is currently in force has been the 
most 
successful of all those agreed in Sarajevo," the president of 
the Srpska republic concluded. 

</TEXT>

