<F P=100> HUNGARY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Translating Material From the Hungarian Minority Press </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  11111111 </F>
<F P=103> 11111111 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
Article   Type:CSO 

  [Text]Translating material from the press of the Hungarian 
minorities in Romania, Slovakia, Serbia, and Ukraine presents 
several difficulties. In the original text, cities and other 
geographic areas are called by their traditional Hungarian 
names, which are usually different from the official names used 
in the majority language. In addition, parties and organizations 
are often designated by unexpanded acronyms, and it is not even 
always clear whether these are derived from the Hungarian or 
from the majority language. Moreover, some designations are 
politically sensitive due to territorial disputes or historical 
considerations. 
  FBIS has adopted the following guidelines for handling such 
material. The guidelines assume that the translator has access 
to the bilingual list of place names published in Budapest: 
(MAGYAR NEVE? Hatarokon tuli helysegnev-szotar; Arany Lapok, 
1990). Since the Ukrainian section of the book gives the Russian 
form and is therefore obsolete, a partial Hungarian/Ukrainian 
list of place names is included below. In addition, lists of 
party and organization acronyms are provided. 
<H5>  I. Use of Bilingual Place Names and Acronyms </H5>
  Translations should give the majority-language form of place 
names and organizations that is approved by the Board of 
Geographic Names (BGN) gazetteer, because this is the 
internationally recognized form found on maps. At the same time, 
the source's use of the Hungarian should be indicated because it 
reflects the original material and may have political 
implications. The following guidelines address both requirements: 
  1. In the headline and subslug, use the majority language 
version of the place or organization (in the latter case, 
usually an acronym). 
  2. In the text, use whatever place name or acronym is used 
in 
the original. If this is in Hungarian, cross-reference the 
majority-language version in a bracketed editorial note on its 
first appearance in the item. 
  3. As is indicated by the above, the English acronym is not 
used. 
  Example: 
  Marko Interviewed at UDMR Conference in Oradea 
  Bucharest ROMANIAI MAGYAR SZO in Hungarian 19 Jun 93 p 9 
  [Interview with Bela Marko, chairman of the Democratic Union 
of Hungarians in Romania, by Janos Szabo in Oradea; date not 
given: "Marko on Future Role of UDMR"] 
  [Text] Shortly after his arrival in Nagyvarad [Oradea], Bela 
Marko, president of the Democratic Union of Hungarians in 
Romania [RMDSZ--in Romanian, UDMR], gave an interview to our 
paper. 
  [Szabo] What do you expect the RMDSZ to achieve here in 
Nagyvarad? 
  [Marko] I hope that we can resolve some of the problems we 
encountered at last month's session in Kolozsvar [Cluj], where 
the Hungarian Smallholders Party of Romania [RMK--in Romanian, 
PMGMR].... 
<H5>  II. List of Acronyms </H5>
  The following lists are incomplete but include most of the 
acronyms used in the Hungarian minority press of these countries 
in 1993. When possible, both the Hungarian and majority-language 
acronyms are listed and cross-referenced because the minority 
press sometimes uses them interchangeably. NOTE: The 
translation of "szovetseg" and several similar words--translated 
variously as union, alliance, federation, and association--could 
not be standardized because of previously established variations 
in common usage. 
<H5>  Romania </H5>
<H5>  Hungarian Organizations </H5>
  EMK = Erdelyi Magyar Kezdemenyezes (Transylvanian Hungarian 
Initiative) 
  FMP = Fuggetlen Magyar Part (Independent Hungarian Party) 
  MAT = Magyar Autonom Tartomany (Hungarian Autonomous 
Territory--historical ref.) 
  MISZ(SZ) = Magyar Ifjusagi Szervezetek (Szovetsege) 
(Federation of Hungarian Youth (Organizations) 
  MURE = Magyar Ujsagirok Romaniai Egyesulete (Association of 
Hungarian Journalists in Romania) 
  PMGMR = RMK (see below) 
  RMDSZ = Romaniai Magyarok Demokratikus Szovetsege 
(Democratic Union of Hungarians in Romania-- UDMR in Romanian) 
  RMGSZ = Romaniai Magyar Gazdak Egyesulete (Association of 
Hungarian Farmers in Romania) 
  RMSZ = Romaniai Magyar Szo (Hungarian daily published in 
Bucharest) 
  RMK = Romaniai Magyar Kisgazdapart (Hungarian Smallholders 
Party of Romania-- PMGMR in Romanian) 
  RMKDP = Romaniai Magyar Keresztenydemokrata Part (Hungarian 
Christian Democratic Party of Romania) 
  SZKT = Szovetsegi Kuldottek Tanacsa (Union Council of 
Delegates) NOTE: This is the supreme decisionmaking body 
of the RMDSZ. It used to be called the Kuldottek Orszagos 
Tanacsa--KOT). 
  UDMR = RMDSZ (see above) 
