<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Izetbegovic: Serbs Not Observing Ultimatum </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2402193294 Paris AFP in English 1924 GMT 24 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2402193294 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Sarajevo, Feb 24 (AFP) -- Bosnian President Alija 
Izetbegovic charged here Thursday that Serbs have failed to 
honor the NATO ultimatum to withdraw all artillery from 
Sarjaevo. He said many Serb heavy guns were still in position 
against the mainly Moslem Bosnian capital. 
  In a statement read to reporters by Bosnian Vice President 
Ejup Ganic, Izetbegovic gave a list of weapons not pulled out 
since the NATO ultimatum expired Monday. "According to reliable 
data, the realization of the ultimatum is not accomplished," the 
statement said. 
  It listed sitings by Bosnian sources from Monday to 
Wednesday 
of eight tanks, three armored personnel carriers and at least 16 
artillery pieces in the 20-kilometre (12-mile) exclusion zone 
NATO had called for around Sarajevo by last Monday. NATO 
threatened air strikes as of Monday to destroy the arms. 
Whether these weapons remained Thursday could not be 
immediately confirmed. 
  UN spokesmen here say there is effective compliance since 
Serb forces have been pulling out artillery and have not shelled 
Sarajevo. 
  UN Protection Force (UNPROFOR) spokesman Canadian 
Lieutenant-Colonel Bill Aikman said Thursday, however, that 
there were still at least eight weapons sites to be checked. 
Aikman said there were in addition sites where Serbs were 
refusing to hand over arms to UN troops. 
  Ganic charged that the 260 pieces of artillery UNPROFOR has 
collected so far from the Serbs included many obsolete arms and 
many below the high calibre weapons the Serbs possess. He spoke 
of UN Bosnian commander British General Michael Rose "saying he 
was going to go to sleep comfortably (at the time the deadline 
fell Monday at 0100 GMT) since the job was done." "Now it is a 
mess," Ganic said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

