<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   UN General Blames Bosnian Army </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2502104994 Paris AFP in English 1024 GMT 25 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2502104994 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Sarajevo, Feb 25 (AFP) -- UN commander for Sarajevo 
French General Andre Soubirou on Friday blamed ceasefire 
violations here on provocations by the mainly Moslem Bosnian 
army. 
  In a statement read out to reporters by a French officer, 
Soubirou said trench digging by Bosnian soldiers drew fire from 
Serbs who thought the Bosnians were trying to advance their 
lines. 
  "The cease-fire is overall respected. However some shots 
fired break it from time to time," Soubirou said in the 
statement read by Major Guy Vinet. "Most often they are the 
result of Serb reaction from anxious soldiers who shoot at the 
Muslims who dig some trenches regularly. These diggings are a 
Bosnian provocation," the statement said. 
  The ceasefire between Serbs besieging Sarajevo and the 
Bosnians defending it was agreed by the two sides on February 9, 
the day NATO issued an ultimatum for heavy artillery to be 
withdrawn from Sarajevo. 
  The ceasefire has held and Sarajevo is the calmest it has 
been since war began in April 1992. Meanwhile a nation-wide 
ceasefire in Moslem-Croat fighting was due to take effect at 
1100 GMT Friday. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

