<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Delegation Leaves for Washington Negotiations </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2502133294 Zagreb Radio Croatia Network in Serbo-Croatian 
1200 GMT 25 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2502133294 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb Radio Croatia Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] Three Croatian politicians have left Frankfurt 
for Washington following an invitation from U.S. Secretary of 
Warren Christopher, including Mate Granic, Croatian deputy prime 
minister and foreign affairs minister. Mate Granic is to have 
talks tomorrow with U.S. Government representatives and with his 
U.S. counterpart Warren Christopher. 
  A Croat republic of Herceg-Bosna delegation is traveling 
together with Minister Granic. It is led by Kresimir Zubak, 
president of the Presidential Council [of the Croat republic of 
Herceg-Bosna] and justice and administration minister. 
Presidential Council member Mile Akmadzic is also traveling with 
him. 
  In Washington they are going to discuss a possible agreement 
between Croats and Muslims and putting an end to the war. 
[passage omitted] 
  The Croatian side will display a high degree of flexibility 
and will do everything for a Croat-Muslim agreement to be 
reached, in which the United States and the European Union are 
interested, most of all the Croat and the Muslim nations, 
Minister Granic said in Frankfurt this afternoon. We will bear 
in mind that the fundamental interests of the Croat people in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina must be completely protected. We have won 
support for our stands from numerous important European 
countries. We are beginning the negotiations in good faith that 
an agreement is possible, and that reaching an agreement would 
mean the beginning of the end of the war and the restoration of 
a permanent peace. This agreement would give a chance to the 
third side [Serbs] to take their standpoint toward a future life 
together in Bosnia-Herzegovina that will be based on equality of 
the three nations, Minister Granic stated for Croatian media 
prior to his departure from Frankfurt. 

</TEXT>

