<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Serbian Krajina, Croatia Extend Truce </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  94P20404B Belgrade VECERNJE NOVOSTI in Serbo-Croatian 1 Feb 
94 p 5 </F>

<F P=103> 94P20404B </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade VECERNJE NOVOSTI </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:CSO 

<F P=106> [Article by J.B.: "Truce Extended"] </F>
  [Text] Two days ago in Knin representatives of the general 
staff of the Serbian Krajina army signed the second consecutive 
agreement to extend the Christmas truce. 
  The first extension of the truce, signed on 13 January 1994 
at the Turanj border crossing near Karlovac, expired last 
midnight. The second, newly signed extension is only a 
continuation of the previously signed agreements, and it will be 
in effect until the end of February. 
  This signing in Knin two days ago was mediated by UNPROFOR 
representatives, as was the previous signing in Zagreb. 
  This latest agreement, according to the general staff of the 
Serbian army of Krajina, provides for a cease-fire and readiness 
to continue negotiations until a general cease-fire is achieved. 
  Armed clashes on the Knin front have significantly decreased 
since 23 December of last year, when the Christmas truce took 
effect. Croatian forces at the Benkovac-Zadar front did not 
observe the cease-fire. Military clashes in this North Dalmatian 
theater continued almost uninterrupted, but they are 
considerably less intense than before. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

