<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Federal </F>
<H3> <TI>   Jovanovic Welcomes Yeltsin's Initiative </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2502124094 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1044 GMT 25 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2502124094 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Kragujevac, 25 Feb (TANJUG) -- There are several 
mutually conflicting initiatives at the moment. None of them is 
fully articulated, but it is obvious that the Russian initiative 
is the most serious one as it requires that the issue of the 
former Bosnia-Herzegovina be resolved at a summit between the 
major powers, or rather the most responsible powers, Yugoslav 
Foreign Affairs Minister Vladislav Jovanovic stated in the 
Hallmark of Time program broadcast on Kragujevac Radio [Serbia]. 
  The fact is, the federal foreign minister said, that there 
is 
no other place that is more suitable nor any other participants 
more competent to take steps toward peace. 
  Commenting on other proposals, and the West's refusal to 
offer support to the Russian initiative, Jovanovic said: "There 
have been some proposals favoring small steps and referring to 
lower level meetings under the pretext that larger steps require 
longer preparation. It is difficult to say whether they are 
only a way to prevent the acceptance of the Russian initiative, 
or whether they are guided by rational reasons. At the moment 
it seems to be more important to prevent the Russian initiative 
than to offer another alternative plan that would be as good and 
as useful." 

</TEXT>

