<F P=100> POLAND </F>
<H3> <TI>   Defense Minister Views `Partnership' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2402184294 Bucharest DIMINEATA in Romanian 22 Feb 94 p 5 </F>
<F P=103> AU2402184294 </F>
<F P=104>  Bucharest DIMINEATA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Romanian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report on interview with Polish Defense </F>
Minister Piotr Kolodziejczyk; place and date not given: "The 
Polish Minister of Defense: `Partnership for Peace Is Less Than 
I Expected...'"] 
  [Text] In an interview granted to ROMPRES national news 
agency, Polish Minister of Defense Piotr Kolodziejczyk said, in 
connection with his country's participation in the "Partnership 
for Peace" [PFP] initiative and NATO integration: 
  "The PFP concept is less than I expected, but it also 
represents an essential step in an adequate direction. It is 
the beginning of the road to the aim pursued, namely to a 
European security system. We are counting on mutual contacts 
between the Polish Army and the armies of the NATO countries and 
we favor joint maneuvers; for the time being, at the lowest 
tactical levels. We are trying in various ways to become 
acquainted with and get used to each other. In this sense, we 
are creating numerous opportunities, the West is doing the same, 
and this inspires us with moderate optimism." 
  In connection with the stage of Polish-Romanian military 
relations and their development, the Polish defense minister 
said: 
  "Were we to check the history of the two peoples, we would 
find numerous elements of friendship, fruitful cultural 
contacts, economic, and, of course, military cooperation. Now, 
we are jointly solving problems linked to higher military 
training and improving cooperation between our topographical 
services and in the area of health care. We are relying on 
technical cooperation. The access by our two countries to the 
PFP initiative is opening up new opportunities for cooperation." 

</TEXT>

