<F P=100> POLAND </F>
<H3> <TI>   New Military Intelligence Appointments </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2402230094 Warsaw PAP in Polish 1916 GMT 24 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2402230094 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw PAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Polish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Warsaw, 24 Feb -- Major General Boleslaw Izydorczyk 
was on Thursday appointed to the post of head of the National 
Defense Ministry office for intelligence services affairs by the 
National Defense minister, National Defense Ministry press 
spokesman, Colonel Wielsaw Rozbicki, reported on 24 February. 
  Command of the executive structures of these services, 
answerable to the chief of the Polish Army General Staff, has 
been entrusted to Colonel Konstanty Malejczyk, the communique 
passed to PAP by the spokesman reads. 
  General Izydorczyk was born in Lodz in 1943. He completed 
higher studies at the Military Technical Academy in Warsaw in 
1968. From 1970 to 1973 he served in the operational and 
training section of the staff of the deputy chief of the Polish 
Army General Staff responsible for economic and technical 
affairs. He took part in UN peace missions, in the office of 
the United Nations peacekeeping forces in the Middle East-Suez 
and also the UN force staff for the observation of the 
separation of forces in Damascus. 
  From 1978 to 1981 he served in the second department of the 
Polish Army General Staff. In the years 1982-84 he was the 
deputy military attache at the Polish Embassy in Washington. In 
the years 1985-88 he again served in the second department of 
the Polish Army General Staff. He was inter alia a military 
observer in the framework of the implementation of the CSCE 
process and the Stockholm document. From 1988 to 1990 he was 
head of the international group of military observers in the UN 
mission in Namibia. From 1990 to 1991, he was deputy chief of 
the board of the Military Foreign Services. From 1991 to 1992 
he filled the post of head of the board in the command of the 
Military Intelligence Services; from June 1992 he was the head 
of the Military Intelligence Services. He is married with two 
daughters. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

