<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Croatia's Granic Meets With Human Rights Group </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2402173994 Bern Swiss Radio International in English 1700 
GMT 24 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2402173994 </F>
<F P=104>  Bern Swiss Radio International </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Croatia's Foreign Minister Mate Granic has called 
for continuing dialogue in order to find a lasting solution to 
the armed conflict in the former Yugoslavia. Granic told the 
United Nations Human Rights Commission in Geneva that 
negotiations were the only way to end the war and find a 
political settlement to the crisis in Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  However Granic, who is also deputy prime minister, made no 
reference to Wednesday's statement by ethnic Croatians in Bosnia 
that they were willing to consider a union with Bosnia's 
Muslims. Croatians and Muslims in Bosnia have agreed a 
cease-fire, which comes into effect at midday on Friday. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-31872 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu038aa_94002" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-038 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  25 February 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Comments on Violations Examined </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2402232794 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1859 GMT 24 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2402232794 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" item] </F>
  [Text] Geneva, Feb 24 (TANJUG) -- Croatian Vice-Premier and 
Foreign Minister Mate Granic on Thursday made an unconvincing 
attempt to absolve Zagreb from responsibility and attribute it 
to the Serbs. 
  Without denying that the Serbs' humanitarian rights have 
been 
violated on a large scale in Croatia, as confirmed in the latest 
reports by the U.N. special rapporteur Tadeusz Mazowiecki and 
the U.S. State Department, in a speech to the U.N. Human Rights 
Commission in Geneva, Granic attempted to find an excuse in 
saying that "Serb armed forces still hold one-third of the 
Croatian territory." 
  Granic said that human rights have been violated as 6,900 
people had been killed, 26,000 others wounded and 7,600 people 
perished in war (which broke out following Croatia's violent 
secession from former Yugoslavia), and that there were currently 
some 550,000 refugees and displaced people in Croatia. 
  Granic, however, failed to explain what this had in common 
with mass evictions of Serbs from their homes, with destruction 
of their property, with discharging them, and especially with 
banning the non-Croat children to attend classes, all of these 
listed in Mazowiecki's report as drastic examples of violation 
of human rights. 
  International humanitarian organizations, including the 
Croatian Helsinki Committee for the Protection of Human Rights, 
have warned intermittently that these actions spurred on ethnic 
cleansing campaigns against the Serbs, 300,000 of them already 
expelled from Croatia. This was why 10,000 Serb houses have 
been blown up and scores of Christian Orthodox churches 
destroyed in Croatia. 
  Granic assessed that the normalisation of relations with 
"the 
Serb minority in Croatia, especially in the U.N. protected 
areas" was "a key to stability in the area and in overall 
Croatian-Serb relations," and threatened in a familiar way that 
there should be no delusions that the Croatian Government would 
negotiate Croatia's territorial integrity. 
  In 1991, Serbs in Croatia proclaimed the Republic of Serb 
Krajina (R.S.K.), now a U.N. protected area, within their ethnic 
and historic territory in response to Croatia's violent 
secession from the former Yugoslavia and its attempt to reduce 
their status to that of a national minority. 
  Serbs in Croatia also decided to take such a step because 
they were afraid of a relapse of the genocide committed against 
them in World War Two, when in the Nazi puppet "independent 
state of Croatia," more than a million Serb civilians had been 
killed. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

