<H3> <TI>   Foreign Minister Cited on Vojvodina Hungarians </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2502215894 Budapest Kossuth Radio Network in Hungarian 
1700 GMT 25 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2502215894 </F>
<F P=104>  Budapest Kossuth Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Hungarian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] The institutionalized protection of minority 
rights was discussed at the Budapest consultation of youth 
organizations of the European Democratic Union. [passage 
omitted] Attila Kert reports: 
  [Kert] Foreign Minister Geza Jeszenszky has spoken, among 
other things, about collective rights. Referring to his recent 
visit to Belgrade, he spoke with cautious optimism about the 
cultural autonomy efforts of the Hungarians in Vojvodina 
[Vajdasag]. He said that negotiations with President Milosevic 
can give rise to some optimism. 
  At the same time, the foreign minister said it was 
regrettable that the draft law on ensuring parliamentary seats 
for the representatives of the ethnic minorities in Hungary was 
not adopted in the Hungarian National Assembly by the required 
two-thirds majority. He stressed, however, that even now the 
Hungarian National Assembly had currently as many as 30 members 
from various nationalities. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

