<H3> <TI>   Velasquez on Defense Minister's Retirement Decision </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA3001014694 Caracas Venezolana de Television Network in 
Spanish 0000 GMT 30 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA3001014694 </F>
<F P=104>  Caracas Venezolana de Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From "The News" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Defense Minister Vice Admiral Radames Munoz Leon 
has asked Head of State Ramon J. Velasquez to irrevocably accept 
his retirement from the national Armed Forces. Along with 
members of the military High Command, Munoz placed his post at 
the president's disposal. The defense minister adopted this 
stand because President-elect Rafael Caldera decided to 
reorganize the military High Command. 
  Meanwhile, President Ramon J. Velasquez said that the work 
done by these soldiers over the past months was decisive in 
preserving democracy. He added that President Caldera is fully 
empowered to make the changes he deems necessary. 
  [Begin Velasquez recording] I wish to say that the military 
High Command and the defense minister have been key 
collaborators in the process that led to the 5 December 
elections. For seven months, months which were filled with 
difficulties, the presence of the military High Command meant 
support and strong stability for the government I headed. 
Holding elections in December was also the High Command's main 
goal. 
  I hold you in high esteem for the work you did, the way you 
have maintained discipline within the military institution, and 
your high sense of patriotism which guides each one of you as 
members of a key team within the national Armed Forces. [end 
recording] 

</TEXT>

