<H3> <TI>   Munoz Denies Ever Wanting To Stage Coup </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA3101021494 Caracas Venezolana de Television Network in 
Spanish 0035 GMT 31 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA3101021494 </F>
<F P=104>  Caracas Venezolana de Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From "The News" newscast] </F>
  [Text] While President Ramon J. Velasquez' last Council of 
Ministers meeting was being held at Miraflores Palace, Vice 
Admiral Radames Munoz [outgoing defense minister] said that 
after the statement he made yesterday he had nothing to add. 
Nevertheless, he rejected the statements made about him by 
reporter Jose Vicente Rangel during a television program. Here 
is what Vice Admiral Radames Munoz said: 
  [Begin Munoz recording] If I had ever thought about staging 
a 
coup d'etat, I had 271 days to do so. Gentlemen, simply by 
taking advantage of the incident that occurred at the 
presidential palace and by arresting one parliament member I 
could have staged a coup. I never perpetrated this and I never 
wanted to, even though in the media there were suggestions that 
I had ordered something like that. I did not do this precisely 
because of my respect for the Venezuelan people and the 
democratic system in which I have a firm belief. Therefore, 
those accusations are groundless. [end recording] 

