<F P=100> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   Aeronautics Minister Confirms Piranha Missile Project </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY2901010794 Sao Paulo O ESTADO DE SAO PAULO in Portuguese 
28 Jan 94 p B10 </F>

<F P=103> PY2901010794 </F>
<F P=104>  Sao Paulo O ESTADO DE SAO PAULO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Portuguese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by Julio Ottonboni] </F>
  [Text] Sao Jose dos Campos -- Aeronautics Minister Lelio 
Vianna Lobo yesterday confirmed the reactivation of the Piranha 
(MAA-1) Missile-Air-1 project, as anticipated by O ESTADO DE SAO 
PAULO. The Piranhas will be fitted onto patrol fighter planes 
by mid-1996 after being built by the Mectron Engenharia and 
receiving approval from the Navy institutes. This is a priority 
project for the Aeronautics Ministry, which wishes to replace 
the 150 U.S. missiles purchased 20 years ago that still equip 
Brazilian combat planes. Brigadier Nelson Taveira, director of 
the Aerospace Technical Center (CTA), said that there is the 
possibility of exporting these missiles. The initial production 
capability will be 10 missiles per month. With a fund of $8.8 
million, the Piranha is being developed by engineers from the 
Aeronautical Technology Institute (ITA). Mectron will review 
the electronic parts and the missile guide control. As this is 
a teleguided weapon, parts of its plans will be modernized with 
the help of the CTA experts. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

