<F P=100> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   Two Commissions Created To Promote Ties With Argentina </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY2901023694 Sao Paulo GAZETA MERCANTIL in Portuguese 28 Jan 
94 p 5 </F>

<F P=103> PY2901023694 </F>
<F P=104>  Sao Paulo GAZETA MERCANTIL </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Portuguese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by Maria Helena Tachinardi] </F>
  [Text] Brasilia -- Brazil and Argentina will create two new 
commissions: one for economic and commercial affairs and one 
for integration and cooperation affairs. In addition, they will 
study other ways to promote contacts between lawmakers, 
academicians, and entrepreneurs. 
  Diplomatic teams from Brazil and Argentina ended a meeting 
on 
Tuesday in Rio de Janeiro. The main issues addressed at the 
meeting were the political, economic, and commercial relations 
between the two countries; Mercosur [Common Market of the South] 
affairs; the coming into force of NAFTA; Argentina's intention 
to create a peace operations center; and the Brazilian desire to 
study a similar initiative for the purpose of promoting the 
approach between the military of the two countries. 
  The Brazilian team was headed by Foreign Ministry Secretary 
General Roberto Abdenur, whose interlocutor was Argentine Vice 
Foreign Minister Fernando Petrella. The meetings were also 
attended by officials in charge of the economic and political 
planning areas of the two foreign ministries. 
  According to Abdenur, the idea is to create a true system of 
consultation so that integration reaches not only the 
governments but also other social sectors. In order to show the 
degree of proximity between the two governments, Abdenur said 
that presidents Itamar Franco and Carlos Menem have already met 
seven times. 
<H5>  Warren Christopher </H5>
  Argentine and Brazilian diplomats also agreed on the 
significance of the conference of nations of the hemisphere that 
the U.S. Government has proposed for this year. Concerning the 
postponement of U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher's 
visit to Brazil, Chile, Argentina, Colombia, and Venezuela, 
Abdenur said that no specific date had been established for the 
tour, and that it should be made in the near future. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

