<F P=100> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   Miltary Officers Depart for Mozambique To Join Un 
Peacekeeping Force </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY2901170094 Madrid EFE in Spanish 1904 GMT 28 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> PY2901170094 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Brasilia, 28 Jan (EFE) -- Official sources have 
reported that 19 Brazilian Armed Forces officers left on 28 
January for Mozambique to join the UN peacekeeping mission under 
way in that country. 
  These Brazilian Army and Air Force officers will replace 
colleagues who have already served one year of peacekeeping duty 
and are about to return to Brazil. 
  Some 146 Brazilian military and police officers are carrying 
out nonmilitary duties -- observation, medical support and 
management -- in five of the 14 UN peacekeeping operations. 
Brazilians are working in Angola, El Salvador, Mozambique, the 
former Yugoslavia and on the Rwanda-Uganda border. 
  The Brazilian Government has asked Congress for permission 
to 
increase its contribution to the peacekeeping force in 
Mozambique by sending 25 police officers and 100 Army privates. 

</TEXT>

