<F P=100> Guatemala </F>
<H3> <TI>   STOJ Not To `Budge' From U.S. Embassy </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2801191894 Guatemala City Cadena de Emisoras Unidas in 
Spanish 1815 GMT 28 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2801191894 </F>
<F P=104>  Guatemala City Cadena de Emisoras Unidas </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From "News Patrol" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Alirio Cifuentes, secretary of the Judicial Branch 
Workers Union [STOJ], says that peasants who have loans with the 
Penny Foundation [Fundacion del Centavo] will not budge from the 
U.S. embassy until their problems are definitively resolved. 
  [Begin Cifuentes recording] The peasants who arrived from 
different communities are still standing across from the U.S. 
Embassy building, waiting for an answer from delegates appointed 
by the president of the Republic to mediate the conflict. The 
meeting is taking place at the Labor Ministry with the 
participation of the labor and agriculture ministers, a human 
rights ombudsman delegate, and, of course, delegates from the 
Penny Foundation, AID, and STOJ. 
  The worrisome part of this issue is that the U.S. Embassy 
has 
refused to examine the conflict in a reasonable manner. AID is 
part of the United States of America, it is part of the U.S. 
Embassy, and if AID donated $11 million to the Penny Foundation 
to set the land project in motion, we cannot explain why it is 
now claiming that it is not in any way involved in the conflict, 
which it says is strictly between the STOJ, peasants, and the 
Penny Foundation. 
  The embassy tells us that if there are any problems we 
should 
file a lawsuit at the competent courts but our position is that 
the funds donated to the Penny Foundation should be supervised 
by AID, which is part of the U.S. Embassy. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

