<F P=100> Guatemala </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government: Strike Failed; Unions Claim Success </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2901030994 Panama City ACAN in Spanish 0112 GMT 29 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA2901030994 </F>
<F P=104>  Panama City ACAN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Guatemala City, 28 Jan (ACAN-EFE) -- According to 
the government, today's strike called by Guatemalan public 
administration workers to demand a 40 percent salary increase 
and to reject the upcoming Sunday referendum was "a failure." 
The unions, however, called the strike "a success." There were 
no violent incidents during the strike. Official sources report 
that the central government has approximately 180,000 employees, 
with another 100,000 from decentralized institutions. 
  Meanwhile, the government called the protest movement 
intended to undermine the referendum a "failure." If approved, 
it will make possible reforming the Constitution to hold the 
parliamentary elections ahead of schedule, change the Supreme 
Court of Justice magistrates, and reduce the president's term 
from five to four years. 
  Government Minister Arnoldo Ortiz has reported that work in 
government institutions is proceeding normally, with the 
exception of two or three of them. Ortiz said the union leaders 
made the mistake of calling the strike for political reasons 
rather than labor-related reasons and this is what caused the 
strike to fail. 
  Armando Sanchez, secretary general of the National 
Federation 
of State Workers Unions, told the press that 90 percent of the 
workers went on strike and that the protest will be resumed 
Monday if their demands are not met. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

