<F P=100> Guatemala </F>
<H3> <TI>   Officials Outline Security Measures for Referendum </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2901000794 Guatemala City SIGLO VEINTIUNO in Spanish 28 
Jan 94 p 9 </F>

<F P=103> PA2901000794 </F>
<F P=104>  Guatemala City SIGLO VEINTIUNO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Yesterday, Army spokesperson Berta Edith Vargas de 
Marroquin reported the National Army will carry out a "military 
control at a distance" operation in the capital's area given the 
upcoming referendum on Sunday. 
  The Government Ministry is responsible for the citizens' 
safety in order for the people to be able to exercise their 
right to vote in an appropriate atmosphere, although the Army is 
providing its cooperation in a coordinated way. 
  The actions will include patrols along roads used by people 
traveling from one place to another, and the number of Army 
forces will be increased accordingly in certain areas. Although 
she did not specify the number of soldiers that would directly 
participate in this operation, she said a special operation has 
become traditional for electoral events in recent years. She 
also said tranquillity and a peaceful electoral process should 
be expected on Sunday due to the work done by civilian security 
and military forces. 
  Members of the Attorney General's Office reported certain 
people have plans to obstruct the referendum; they said it 
involves groups that are interested is preventing the event. 
They added: Investigations conducted into recent terrorist 
attacks indicate unfortunate events may occur on Sunday, 30 
January. Therefore, a contingency plan was prepared to guarantee 
the Guatemalan people's safety. 
  Carlos Alvarez, a member of the Public Prosecutor's Office, 
and Claudio Porres, investigations director at the Attorney 
General's Office, said the plan will be executed on a national 
level and will include all security forces. 
  Public prosecutors and investigators will also be deployed 
in 
strategic areas so they may immediately proceed to arrest people 
or groups found perpetrating criminal actions. The officials 
said: Likewise, we have information that members of the 
government worker unions will carry out demonstrations, but they 
will be immediately arrested and arraigned if they violate the 
law. "We trust the groups that have called for demonstrations 
will reconsider their decision and allow the people to freely 
cast their ballots so everything may be carried out normally," 
Alvarez and Porres said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

