<F P=100> Guatemala </F>
<H3> <TI>   Polling Stations Open for Constitutional Referendum </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA3001135094 Panama City ACAN in Spanish 1315 GMT 30 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA3001135094 </F>
<F P=104>  Panama City ACAN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Guatemala City, 30 Jan (ACAN-EFE) -- Guatemala's 
polling stations opened their doors at 0700 (1300 GMT) today, 
Sunday, so that 3.4 million potential voters may have their say 
in the 1985 constitutional reform proposal. 
  If the yes vote wins, the Constitution will be changed and 
the legislative elections will be moved up, the Supreme Court of 
Justice will be changed, and the term for holders of public 
office will be reduced, among other measures. 
  Approximately 20 international observers, delegates from 
human rights organizations, and police and Army forces are 
watching so that the referendum will be held normally. The 
referendum has been preceded by a wave of bomb attacks in recent 
days. No one has claimed credit for these attacks. 
  President Ramiro de Leon and the Congress deputies have 
agreed on a referendum to end the confrontation the executive 
branch and Congress had last year, when congressmen refused to 
resign as the chief of state had asked to "purge" institutional 
corruption. 
  De Leon and the country's most important political parties 
have called for a "yes" vote to the reforms, but the left and 
the guerrillas--the only ones left in Central America and that 
have been armed since 1960--have urged the people to abstain 
from voting and to boycott the referendum, because they do not 
believe it will resolve the country's political and economic 
problems. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-31943 </DOCNO>
