<F P=100> Guatemala </F>
<H3> <TI>   First Hour of Voting Marked by Abstention, Propaganda </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA3001152194 Panama City ACAN in Spanish 1445 GMT 30 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA3001152194 </F>
<F P=104>  Panama City ACAN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Guatemala City, 30 Jan (ACAN-EFE) -- According to 
several sources, the first hour of voting has been characterized 
by abstention and guerrilla propaganda against the 
constitutional reforms being voted on today in Guatemala in a 
referendum. 
  Alleged Guatemalan National Revolutionary Unity (URNG) 
members scattered fliers in the city's outskirts calling on the 
people to reject the reforms. 
  Several streets were littered during the predawn hours with 
other fliers in favor of the reforms. 
  Campaigning in favor or against the 43 constitutional 
reforms 
was prohibited by the Supreme Electoral Tribunal (TSE) since 
noon 28 January. 
  TSE Magistrate Mario Guerra Roldan has said to carry out any 
campaigning either for the "yes" or "no" vote, which includes 
moving ahead the date of the legislative elections, is against 
the electoral process. 
  Meanwhile, abstention marks the first hour of voting, and 
according to radio reports, the number of people who have gone 
to polling stations installed in various schools in Guatemala 
City averaged between three to seven. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

