<H3> <TI>   Officials Comment on Referendum Voting </TI></H3>
<H4>   President De Leon </H4>
<F P=102> PA3001171294 Guatemala City Cadena de Emisoras Unidas in 
Spanish 1600 GMT 30 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA3001171294 </F>
<F P=104>  Guatemala City Cadena de Emisoras Unidas </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [News Conference by Guatemalan President Ramiro de Leon </F>
Carpio with unidentified reporters at the University Auditorium 
polling station in Guatemala City on 30 January--recorded] 
  [Text] [De Leon] There is calm here and in the country's 
interior. I have just been informed that everything is normal, 
and the people are participating. 
  [Reporter] But participation.... 
  [De Leon, interrupting] We do not know that yet because 
participation.... 
  [Reporter, interrupting] [Words indistinct] if the yes vote 
wins? 
  [De Leon] This would demonstrate that the Guatemalan people 
have ratified what they demanded following the 25 May events: 
the purging of state organizations, Congress, and the Supreme 
Court, and the restructuring of [word indistinct]. This will be 
the first.... 
  [Reporter, interrupting] [Words indistinct]. 
  [De Leon] Political stability and calm that will allow us to 
govern and to face important social and economic problems 
through a government plan we have drafted. 
  [Reporter] Mr. President, do you have any preliminary report 
from the interior? 
  [De Leon] Of course. Fortunately everything is going 
normally, calmly. We do not know how many people are voting, 
but the truth is that despite all the terrorist problems, 
obstacles, pressure, and efforts to boycott the event, the 
referendum is taking place. The fact that the event is taking 
place strengthens the democratic system, because this is an 
example to the world. While in other countries domestic 
problems are resolved antidemocratically, through violence, here 
in Guatemala we are resolving this national political problem 
democratically, the most sacred way the people have as the 
expression of their sovereignty: through votes. 

</TEXT>

