<F P=100> Guatemala </F>
<H3> <TI>   Polls Close; Abtentionism Reportedly 20-25 Percent </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA3101001294 Panama City ACAN in Spanish 2326 GMT 30 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA3101001294 </F>
<F P=104>  Panama City ACAN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Guatemala City, 30 Jan (ACAN-EFE) -- Voting in the 
referendum held today in Guatemala to reform the constitution 
and replace the Parliament and Supreme Court concluded nearly 
everywhere in the country. It was characterized by high 
abstentionism and an absence of major incidents. 
  The presidents of several voting tables in the urban and 
rural areas estimated the turnout at 20-25 percent at closure 
time. 
  One of the first tables to yield results in Totonicapan 
reported, according to local reporters, 71 yes votes, 18 no 
votes, and 35 void votes, and was marked by very high 
abstentionism that was not quantified. 

</TEXT>

