<F P=100> Guatemala </F>
<H3> <TI>   Initial Results: `Yes' Vote Winning, High Abstentionism </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA3101020394 Panama City ACAN in Spanish 0124 GMT 31 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA3101020394 </F>
<F P=104>  Panama City ACAN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Guatemala City, 31 Jan (ACAN) -- The initial count 
by the Supreme Electoral Tribunal (TSE) in the Guatemalan 
capital shows a victory for the "yes" vote in today's referendum 
on 43 constitutional reforms and a high abstention rate of 73.3 
percent. 
  The TSE said that with 6 percent of the 1,122 polling 
stations in the capital counted, the "yes" vote obtained 13.62 
percent and the "no" vote 3.22 percent. Abstentionism reached 
73.3 percent in this initial count in the metropolitan area. 
  The TSE also reported that in Totonicapan Department, where 
125 polling stations were located, 1,845 people voted for the 
reforms and 404 voted against them. 

</TEXT>

