<F P=100> Ecuador </F>
<H3> <TI>   Students, Police Clash Over Anticipated Increase </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2901002494 Quito Voz de los Andes in Spanish 2300 GMT 28 
Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2901002494 </F>
<F P=104>  Quito Voz de los Andes </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From "The Voz Andes" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Quito -- At least three policemen were injured and 
an undisclosed number of students were arrested in the wake of 
protests staged here today in the face of announced economic 
adjustment measures. The demonstrators, mostly students from the 
Central University of Ecuador and some from certain secondary 
schools, were repelled with tear gas and a water cannon known as 
Trucutu. 
  Security measures were tightened at the Government Palace. 
Nearby roads were blocked with Army armored vehicles. The 
students are throwing rocks and making obscene gestures at the 
policemen, and they are shouting slogans against the government 
and the IMF. 
  We do not want more increases, and we say no to gasoline 
price increases were among the slogans shouted as the 
demonstrators threw rocks and other hard objects at the public 
forces. 
  As we reported earlier, the government will announce fuel 
price increases to cover the large fiscal deficit, which is 
growing by the day given a drop in revenues due to lower 
petroleum prices. Petroleum is Ecuador's main revenue source. 
  The police were forced to close the access roads near the 
university in downtown Quito as well as other streets in the 
southern part of Quito. This has created a huge traffic jam. 
There are long lines at gas stations. 
  It is not yet known whether there are disturbances in 
Guayaquil, the second most important city in our country. Radio 
reports state that more public demonstrations against gasoline 
price increases are expected next week as secondary school 
students join the demonstrations. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

